ODE VI.

In this beautiful ode the poet does not merely describe the pleasures and charms of Spring. His object seems to be toin- culcate a moral Iesson. He would show by the rapid successim of the seasons, and the decay of all things in the vegetable king- dom, that man himself is rapidly passing away3 and that whatever he has to do in this life must be done quickly.
